# infra/optimism-mainnet/.env — Ophis Optimism mainnet secrets.
# COPY this file to .env, fill in the secrets, NEVER COMMIT the populated form.
# .gitignore already excludes infra/optimism-mainnet/.env.
#
# After copying, chmod 600 .env — render-configs.sh enforces this on every
# deploy but the initial copy is on the operator. This keeps the
# OKX credentials owner-only at the filesystem layer.
#
# NOTE (2026-05-18, Tier 1 PK isolation): the driver-submitter PK is no
# longer stored in the macOS Keychain or this .env file. It lives at
# /Users/ophis-driver/.config/submitter.key (0600, owned by ophis-driver
# user). render-configs.sh reads it via sudo at deploy time.
#
# NOTE (2026-05-19, Phase 4 audit M H3 honesty fix): OKX, CoinGecko, and
# Postgres credentials live HERE in this .env at chmod 600. The earlier
# comment claimed OKX creds live in Keychain — that was aspirational,
# never implemented. .env at chmod 600 is the actually-working path.
# Threat model: any process running as scep can read .env. Tier 1.5
# (RAM-disk render) or Tier 2 (per-secret manager) closes this. Until
# then, keep .env on FileVault-encrypted disk + Mac mini's physical
# security as the only barriers.

# ── Database ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Pick a strong random password (32+ chars). Different from testnet (which
# uses '123' for convenience). Generate via:
#   openssl rand -base64 32
POSTGRES_USER=ophis
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=
POSTGRES_DB=ophis
DB_WRITE_URL=postgresql://ophis:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}@db:5432/ophis
DB_READ_URL=postgresql://ophis:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}@db:5432/ophis

# ── Chain RPC ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Phase 4 audit M-2 (2026-05-19): chain reads now flow through the
# eRPC proxy at http://rpc-proxy:4000/main/evm/10 (configured in
# configs/erpc.yaml.tmpl, 3 free upstreams, 2-of-3 consensus on critical
# methods). The OP_MAINNET_RPC env var below is no longer wired into
# any service by default — left as a hint for operators who want to
# bypass eRPC for a quick smoke test:
#   OP_RPC_INTERNAL=https://optimism-rpc.publicnode.com docker compose up -d
OP_MAINNET_RPC=https://optimism-rpc.publicnode.com

# Optional override: if set, ALL chain-reading services point at this URL
# instead of the eRPC proxy. Used for failure-domain tests (e.g. point at
# a single upstream to validate fallback behavior) and emergency bypass if
# eRPC itself misbehaves. Leave empty in normal operation.
OP_RPC_INTERNAL=

# ── Driver-submitter private key ──────────────────────────────────────────
# Corresponds to on-chain address 0x00f98b5776eb0f6a8c0c925ddF51f9Ade8a1502F,
# which was allowlisted in deploy-mainnet-all.sh Step 3 (addSolver). This EOA
# signs every settlement transaction. Treat like a hot-wallet key — keep
# balance bounded (~0.02 OP ETH, top up as needed) to cap blast radius.
#
# DEPRECATED post-Tier-1 PK isolation (2026-05-18). The PK now lives at
# /Users/ophis-driver/.config/submitter.key and is read by render-configs.sh
# directly. Leave this var empty in production .env.
OPHIS_DRIVER_SUBMITTER_KEY=

# ── OKX aggregator solver credentials ─────────────────────────────────────
# All 4 fields are required by apps/backend/crates/solvers OKX module.
# Create at https://web3.okx.com/build → API keys → New key with scopes:
# Trade + Read on the OnchainOS DEX product. Copy each field below.
#
# IMPORTANT: do NOT add a payment method on the OKX dashboard. The API
# caps at the $100 Basic + $50 Premium monthly free quota and stops
# responding (rather than billing) once exceeded. Caps financial risk
# at $0/mo.
#
# Rotation procedure if leaked: OKX dashboard → revoke old key → create
# new with same scopes → update lines below → run render-configs.sh →
# `docker compose restart okx-solver`. Verify with a sample quote via
# orderbook /api/v1/quote.
OKX_PROJECT_ID=
OKX_API_KEY=
OKX_SECRET_KEY=
OKX_PASSPHRASE=

# ── Distributed tracing ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Phase 4 audit M-6 (2026-05-19). The CoW backend's observe crate ships
# opentelemetry-otlp + tonic gRPC export already; docker-compose now runs
# a Jaeger all-in-one (image: jaegertracing/all-in-one) bound to:
#   - http://jaeger:4317  OTLP/gRPC ingest (services use this URL)
#   - http://127.0.0.1:16686  Jaeger UI (operator-facing)
#
# Set the env var below to enable tracing:
#   TRACING_COLLECTOR_ENDPOINT=http://jaeger:4317
#
# Leave empty to disable (tracing_config() returns None and the binaries
# skip the OTLP exporter entirely — zero overhead).
#
# In-memory trace storage: history wipes on jaeger restart. Acceptable
# for current "debug a specific incident" use; promote to persistent
# Badger storage when retention >24h is needed.
TRACING_COLLECTOR_ENDPOINT=

# ── Observability (Prometheus + Alertmanager → Telegram) ─────────────────
# Alertmanager sends `critical` / `warning` alerts to Clement's Telegram
# DM via the Clawdius bot. Token shape: {int}:{base64-ish}.
#
# Phase 1.5 (2026-05-20): PREFERRED token source is macOS Keychain,
# NOT this .env file. Keeps the token off cleartext disk, out of Time
# Machine backups, out of casual `cat .env` exposure.
#
# Setup (one-time):
#   security add-generic-password -a "$USER" -s ophis-telegram-bot \
#     -w '<bot-token>' -U
#
# render-configs.sh checks the Keychain when TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN is unset
# in .env. Token lookup procedure for the value:
#   ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json → channels.telegram.botToken
#
# Leave this var EMPTY when you've put the token in Keychain. Set it
# here only if you have a one-off reason (e.g. testing with a different
# bot) — render-configs.sh respects env-var over Keychain.
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=

# ── Tenderly REST API (Phase 3 functional completeness) ──────────────────
# 2026-05-20: Clement's Tenderly account (san-npm) REST API key.
# Used for pre-broadcast settlement simulation — driver verifies that
# `settle(...)` will succeed BEFORE paying gas. Catches reverts before
# the mempool, saves the 5-gwei-cap budget on bad solutions.
#
# Endpoint: https://api.tenderly.co/api/v1/account/san-npm/project/project/
# Header:   X-Access-Key: ${TENDERLY_API_KEY}
#
# NOT used for the eRPC Gateway. Web3 Gateway needs a separate access
# key (tenderly.co → Web3 Gateway → New Endpoint → Optimism Mainnet).
# When you create that, set TENDERLY_GATEWAY_URL below.
TENDERLY_API_KEY=

# When you create a Tenderly Web3 Gateway for OP, paste the full URL here
# (e.g. https://optimism.gateway.tenderly.co/<gateway-id>). erpc.yaml.tmpl
# will use it as a 3rd upstream and we can re-add eth_getBalance to strict
# consensus.
TENDERLY_GATEWAY_URL=

# ── CoinGecko (native-price oracle for autopilot + orderbook) ─────────────
# Required by docker-compose.yml — autopilot and orderbook fail-fast at
# startup if unset. Get a free key at
# https://www.coingecko.com/en/api/pricing — the free Demo tier allows
# 30 calls/min, 10K calls/month, enough for OP-only operation.
COINGECKO_API_KEY=
